events.name: dun/conman
events.message: Fix out-of-bounds read warnings in server-conf.c Coverity Scan flagged 3 out-of-bound reads in server-conf.c: in parse_console_directive(), parse_global_directive(), and parse_server_directive(). These 3 routines are called from process_config() and follow the same pattern. The directive string is obtained by calling lex_prev(), passing the resulting token enum to the LEX_UNTOK macro, and using the resulting integer to index into the server_conf_strs[] array of strings. The LEX_UNTOK macro does not perform bounds-checking, so directly using its result as an index into server_conf_strs[] could result in an out-of-bounds read. However, this does not actually happen in the code. When these 3 routines are called from process_config(), the resulting value for lex_prev() must be one of SERVER_CONF_CONSOLE, SERVER_CONF_GLOBAL, or SERVER_CONF_SERVER. In all 3 cases, the LEX_UNTOK macro will return a valid index into server_conf_strs[]. But instead of relying on this behavior, this commit adds lex_tok_to_str() which performs proper bounds-checking of the array index when converting a lex token enum into its corresponding string. Use of the LEX_UNTOK macro in these 3 routines is replaced with lex_tok_to_str(). Signed-off-by: Chris Dunlap Coverity ID 1361788 Coverity ID 1361790 Coverity ID 1361799

events.name: dun/conman
events.message: Fix resource leak of sd in connect_to_server In connect_to_server(), a file descriptor is obtained for an unbound socket. If the subsequent call to host_name_to_addr4() or connect() fails, the function will set errnum & errmsg and return -1 without closing the socket descriptor thereby causing a resource leak -- although the function will then immediately return to main(), call display_error(), and terminate. This commit fixes the resource leak of the socket descriptor in connect_to_server(). The return value of close() is discarded since it is in the error handling code. Signed-off-by: Chris Dunlap Coverity ID 1361793 Coverity ID 1367924

This commit fixes the resource leak of the socket descriptor in connect_to_server(). The return value of close() is discarded since it is in the error handling code. events.name: dun/conman
events.message: Setup Travis CI builds This commit enables Travis CI continuous integration builds at . A build matrix is defined to create debug and production builds using gcc and clang compilers. The  - Werror  and  - pedantic - errors  CFLAGS options are specified for all builds in order to change warnings into errors. Note that the --with - freeipmi  configure option is not enabled. The standard Travis CI virtualization environment is based on Ubuntu 12.04, and its version of FreeIPMI is too old to work with ConMan; also, libfreeipmi-dev and libipmiconsole-dev are not on the list of approved packages. Installing a current version of FreeIPMI for the Travis builds is TBD. colormake is used to colorize the output of the Travis CI job log. Reference: - https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/getting-started/ Signed-off-by: Chris Dunlap

events.name: dun/munge
events.message: Specify C99 language standard in debug build The gcc version in Ubuntu 12.04 (used for the standard Travis CI virtualization environment) defaults to the C90 language standard. This causes  - pedantic  builds to fail with the following errors: > unmunge.c: In function 'display_meta': > unmunge.c:627:17: error: ISO C90 does not support the '%z' > gnu_strftime format [-Werror=format] > unmunge.c:651:17: error: ISO C90 does not support the '%z' > gnu_strftime format [-Werror=format] This commit updates the DEBUGCFLAGS specified via --enable - debug  to use the C99 language standard. C99 adds support for the  % z  strftime() conversion specifier. Signed-off-by: Chris Dunlap

events.name: dun/munge
events.message: Setup Travis CI builds This commit enables Travis CI continuous integration builds at . A build matrix is defined to create debug and production builds with libgcrypt and openssl cryptographic libraries using gcc and clang compilers. The  - Werror  CFLAGS option is specified for all builds in order to change warnings into errors. Note that neither  - pedantic  nor  - pedantic - errors  is specified in CFLAGS. libtool will fail if either is used in the CFLAGS passed to the configure script. It should be possible to override libtool's CFLAGS via LTCFLAGS, but this does not work; LTCFLAGS always takes on the value of CFLAGS. Grrr. DISTCHECK_CONFIGURE_FLAGS is needed to pass CONFIGURE_OPTS to the configure script in . Note that the DISTCHECK_CONFIGURE_FLAGS value of CONFIGURE_OPTS is single-quoted in the global environment definition.
